And when a great man dies, what do we play?

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
The funeral march from Beethoven's 

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:08.000
Eroica. And on United Nations Day, or 

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Brotherhood week, or whatever, 

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000
what is the inevitable piece of 

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.000
music? Beethoven's Ninth. Why, even the 

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.000
Beatles featured it in their film "Help." 

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
And look at Schroeder in Peanuts: To him 

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Beethoven's birthday is more important 

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:25.000
than the 4th of July. 

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.000
It's Beethoven, Beethoven, forever 

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
Beethoven - a name that's almost become 

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.000
a synonym for music itself. And who was 

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
this giant with the magic name? 

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:41.000
He was s short, stubby fellow, not Viennese

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
at all, not even Austrian, but German, from 

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
the town of Bonn on the Rhine River, 

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
where he was born in 1770. 

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
At the age of 22 he 

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:55.000
was sent to Vienna by the local big-shots of 

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:56.000
his home town, 

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
since Vienna was the place for music - 

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
for studying and making a career.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
And so this little provincial chap with bad 

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
skin and a comedy accent from the 

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:11.000
Rhineland arrived in Vienna, knocked 

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.000
everyone dead, and was taken up by the 

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Viennese nobility and made a hero.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.000
His fame spread, and he soon dominated the musical scene, 

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:21.000
which he has dominated ever 

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:24.000
since - the mighty, the colossal, the 

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
profound, the revolutionary, the mystic, 

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
romantic Beethoven. 

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
He was also bad-tempered, 

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:38.000
stubborn, ill-mannered, opinionated, 

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.000
moody, and miserly. But out of this homely 

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
human vessel,

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:55.000
a voice spoke that was 

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.000
more than human - a voice with the ring and the 

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:01.000
conviction of something eternal, 

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.000
something that still today makes us 

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
tingle with the certainty that a 

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.000
divine spark exists in every one of us.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Now why should this be? I've been trying all 

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.000
my life to find out. The very first 

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
television program I ever did was 

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
about Beethoven. The very 

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
first chapter of my first book is called 

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
"Why Beethoven?" Well, I'm still asking that 

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:27.000
question, and will probably never find a 

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
total answer. Mighty, colossal - those words 

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.000
just don't explain anything. Because the 

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:36.000
final answer is a mystery - the mystery of 

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
why this one particular 

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:42.000
shaggy-headed little man should have 

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
been chosen to wallop the galaxies with his music.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.000
And so we shall have an all-Beethoven

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:51.000
program today, beginning, as we began 

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.000
125 years ago, with those four heaven-

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.000
storming notes that announce the first 

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:02.000
movement of his Fifth Symphony."

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
Did you grasp 

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.000
the fantastic shape of that movement? The perfect 

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
definition, the exactness, of starts and 

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
stops, of holding back and plunging ahead, 

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
of the sudden mysterious drops and the 

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
wild eruptions? Every split-second is 

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
measured and molded by a master.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.000
And apropos of this shaping, 

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
there is an important thing that needs to 

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
be said, and I'm going to 

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
run the risk of boring you 

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:14.000
with a tiny lecture in order to try to say it. You've 

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
probably heard of a popular biography of 

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
Beethoven called "The Man Who Freed Music."

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
Now this title has always caused me a 

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
certain disquiet. What does it 

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
mean? Freed music from what? From Bach? 

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:30.000
From Nozart? Haydn? Well hardly: 

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.000
they all had plenty of freedom of their 

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.000
own. The truth is that all great composers 

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:39.000
free music - not from the bondage of other 

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.000
composers, but from routine, from 

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
mediocrity, from second-rate, dusty 

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
tradition; in other words, a great 

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.000
composer frees music from the 

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
predictable. Take one of Beethoven's 

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
most obvious examples of the 

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:58.000
unpredictable - the opening tune of 

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:01.000
his third Symphony, the Eroica. 

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.000
It rides along in E-b major on 

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
the nice, expected notes of the tonic 

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:13.000
triad for four bars,

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
and then, on the fifth bar, the unexpected happens:

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:29.000
Bang! - That D-b! Surprise: the bondage of 

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
the Triad is broken. Music is freed. But 

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:35.000
freed by what? By a Db- and that's 

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:36.000
just the point: 

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:39.000
a Db, not a Cb or an A 

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
but that one, chosen, limited note, 

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
Db-that did the freeing.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
Doesn't this tell us something very important 

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
about the nature of freedom? Obviously 

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
freedom must carry with it the meaning 

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.000
of freedom to limit oneself, and one's 

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:00.000
material. Freedom is not infinite, not

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.000
boundless liberty, as some hippies like 

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.000
to think - do anything you want, any time, 

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.000
anywhere you want to. No, freedom 

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:12.000
means being free to make 

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:15.000
decisions, to determine one's course.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:19.000
But decision means choice; 

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:22.000
and choice is impossible without 

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
rejection. Can you understand that? 

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:27.000
You can't choose something without 

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.000
rejecting all the other things you 

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:32.000
haven't chosen. If you choose one 

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
apple out of a dozen, you automatically 

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:38.000
unchoose the other eleven, and if Beethoven 

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
chooses that one D-Flat, he automatically

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:45.000
un-chooses all the other eleven notes.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:49.000
So you see, real freedom must contain 

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
within itself the freedom to un-choose, 

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:55.000
to censor oneself, to limit 

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
oneself. That is the whole meaning of 

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:01.000
democracy, the kind of freedom on which 

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
we base our hopes for a peaceful world - 

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:06.000
just as it is the meaning of freedom in 

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
great musical invention. In Beethoven, 

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
as in democracy, freedom is a discipline,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
combining the right to choose freely,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:19.000
and the gift of choosing wisely. Now do 

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:20.000
you see what I mean by Beethoven's 

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:24.000
masterly shaping of that movement? I hope so! End 

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:28.000
of lecture. Now we are going to hear

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:31.000
more of that great free discipline in 

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
action - the last two movements of 

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:36.000
Beethoven's Fourth Piano Concerto. 

