00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:47.000
We have 

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.000
been talking about the connection 

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.000
between Beethoven and freedom; 

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:54.000
and nowhere is that connection more evident 

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:57.000
than in Beethoven's opera Fidelio. 

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:59.000
This was the only opera Beethoven ever wrote, 

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:01.000
but he wrote it and rewrote it and 

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:04.000
rewrote it over a period of twelve years. 

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:07.000
This, of course, was typical, of Beethoven 

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:09.000
in his search for perfection; all his

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.000
works went through long agonies of 

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:14.000
rewriting and scratching out and trying 

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:17.000
again -that was the price he paid for his 

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:20.000
freedom, the price of free choice - to make 

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:23.000
the exactly right choice. But, with his 

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:25.000
opera Fidelio the agony was even worse, 

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:28.000
and I think one of the main reasons was 

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:29.000
that the story of the opera deals with 

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:32.000
the very subject of freedom itself. 

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:34.000
The hero of the story is a young Spaniard named Florestan, 

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:43.000
who has been unjustly imprisoned for 

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:45.000
speaking out freely against tyranny.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:45.500
The whole opera takes place in the prison where the villainous governor Don Pizzaro has Florestan locked in a dungeon, planning eventually to have him killed. 

00:34:45.500 --> 00:34:48.000
Florestan's faithful wife, 

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:51.000
Leonore, has managed to sneak into the 

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.000
prison disguised as a boy, and gets a job 

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:56.000
as the jailor's assistant so that she can 

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:59.000
help her husband escape. That is the basic plot of the opera.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.000
SKIPPED
And toward the end there is a glorious exciting moment when FIorestan is rescued just as he is about to be killed:	we suddenly hear the far-off
trumpet-call that announces the arrival of the rescue-party; there is a race against time, but the trumpet-call comes nearer, and finally all is saved - freedom triumphs and injustice is punished.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.000
Now why is this opera called Fidelio? 

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:06.000
Because that is the name Leonore takes 

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:10.000
in her disguise as a boy. And even here 

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.000
Beethoven wrestled with 

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:15.000
his freedoms of choice:	The opera was

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:17.000
first called Fidelio and then changed to 

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:19.000
Leonore and then back 

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:22.000
to Fidelio. And the overture to the opera 

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:25.000
most clearly of all reflects the agony 

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:28.000
of free choices:	

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:29.000
there are not one but four overtures to this opera. 

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:36.000
The original one was called, peculiarly enough, Overture to Leonora. But Beethoven was not satisfied with it, and wrote a second Leonore Overture - and then, believe it or not, a whole new third one - Leonore #3.

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:40.000
As if that weren't enough exercise in unchoosing, he finally wound up with a fourth overture, known as the Overture to Fidelio.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:48.000
Out of all four, it is the 3rd Leonore Overture that 

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:50.000
is the masterpiece, and the one we are 

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:53.000
going to play now. It is a massive work - 

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:55.000
more than just an overture, rather 

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:58.000
like a great symphonic poem 

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:00.000
describing the whole opera. During its slow 

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:02.000
introduction we feel the heavy, brooding 

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:05.000
atmosphere of Florestan's dungeon, 

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:07.000
then, when the main fast section begins, 

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:10.000
we hear the gradually rising hope of 

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:12.000
rescue surging up through the orchestra, 

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:14.000
and the excitement is made even more 

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.000
dramatic by alternating with moods of 

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:20.000
prayer and of love music. At the climax 

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:22.000
the orchestra is suddenly cut off, and the 

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:25.000
famous trumpet-call of liberation sounds 

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:28.000
in the distance 

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.000
(You'11 hear it 

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:32.000
coming from somewhere backstage): 

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:34.000
Then there is a moment of hushed 

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:35.000
suspense, then again the trumpet-call, nearer this 

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:40.000
time, and finally the triumphant 

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:42.000
achievement of freedom, in a coda of 

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:46.000
brilliant celebration. As you listen now to 

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:48.000
this essay on liberty, you can 

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:50.000
understand why Beethoven has always 

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:54.000
meant so much to us. 

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:57.000
As long as the human race struggles for 

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:58.000
freedom. 

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:39.000
